rComments: God Bless this man, he is so funny and quirky that the classes are always lively. If you miss the reading he makes it easy to understand in lecture

super charismatic and gives entertaining lectures, but a lot of the time he seems to be grasping at straws/not following a clear train of thought. he despises the traditional essay, so every prompt takes a lot of effort to decipher and you have to be willing to take some creative risks. exam essay question was given in advance but A LOT to unpack.

Warley's enthusiasm makes the love of literature contagious. I looked forward to his lecture every week and found they helped me improve as both a writer and reader. The TAs were also incredibly helpful and thoughtful. All around an incredible course and starting point for English majors.

This prof is a real gem! He really loves what he teaches and that feeling is contagious. It never felt like going to lectures but instead it was like going to the theatre or watch a solo performance. Really inspirational and chooses great works and authors! 100% recommend and I wish he teaches more courses.
One of the best professors I have had so far in English. He has an original way of looking at old texts and makes them appear accessible and interesting.

Love, love, loved this class and would absolutely take it again. Prof. Warley knows how to teach unlike any other in the English department at U of T. If you are an avid reader, don't think twice about taking this class, just do it! I think I learned more from him alone than I have in my entire undergraduate career.

Prof. Warley is truly one of the best teachers I've ever had in my life -- this guy is SO passionate about what he teaches, and his enthusiasm is contagious! He's super nice and approachable in office hours, he works hard to make your experience as a student enjoyable, and he's gorgeous... Take his class, I promise you won't regret it.
He's one of the best profs ive ever had. Passionate about what he teaches, his lectures are very engaging and fun and hes a really nice guy!
Good class. He is very animated and explains the readings well. Clearly passionate about his subjects. Tends to have very specific views on things but is still very interesting.

The content of his course is difficult, but he is a really good lecturer. A fair marker but a bit of a stickler. The work isn't overwhelming, but becomes hard because he isn't specific about what he wants.  He was often hard to talk to and seemed generally distracted. I enjoyed his class but I don't think I would take another with him.

The content is very difficult but he explains and addresses it very well in class, the essays aren't too hard if you've been attending. Very enthusiastic lecturer, it's hard not to pay attention as he speaks wildly and makes huge gestures, but it makes the class interesting and keeps my attention.

Came into the class hating Brit Lit from high school; came out loving it and having a new respect for the work. He seems harsh at first (can't be VERY late or he will question you) but it's within reason. His lectures are inspiring & insightful, definitely can't miss them. Class is dependent on them. One of the best Eng prof I have had at UofT.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Amazing lectures', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Professor Warley is by far and away my favourite professor at U of T. His lectures are brilliant and the entire course is structured to build upon previous lectures. I recommend him to anyone who wants to learn and never fall asleep in class.

Professor Warley is possibly the best thing to ever happen to Renaissance Studies at U of T. He is so engaging and passionate about the topic that it will make you love his field, even if you have no background in it. His classes build upon each other and if you're doing the readings and keeping up, you can start to see the connections he makes.
Lectures are defiantly interesting and clear. You better do your readings and show up to every class though. Or else you'll have a hard time.
Awesome prof! Extremely intelligent, engaging, charismatic and hilarious! Would definitely recommend this guy! Also a fair grader:).

Great class.  Warley's lectures are thought provoking and wildly interesting - the insights he brings to the texts are incredibly illuminating.  You have to be on time or he won't let you in class but definitely worth the eccentricities.
teacherRatingTags: ['Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Chris Warley is a professor that cares about literature and will inspire you to care. He pushes you to think more, read better, and does an incredible job tying things together (e.g. your life, Paradise Lost, the weather). About the lateness policy: he wants to be respected. Tell him if you think you'll be late for a good reason. He'll understand.

If anyone is late, he makes the student stand in front of the class, explain why, and apologize. I understand disliking interruptions  but forcing students to divulge their personal life is disgusting; he uses fear tactics to run his lectures. There is an endless list of legitimate why someone might be late in such a diverse student population.

Warley is brilliant and completely engaging - lectures were always over way too soon and I was never ready to leave. No matter how competent a reader you (think you) are, Warley will take you to a whole new level. Take any course he's teaching!

Warley is a pretty competent cheerleader for Milton n Donne. He'll bother to ask who you are if you go to his office. Beware, however, to be on time for lectures and not to be reading a newspaper. More than anything, he has converted me to be a philologist. In any case, you don't need coffee for his Clooney performance of Sir Gawain at 11 am.

I don't get the Warley hype. Loves to hear his own voice and humble brag incessantly. You better like what he likes -- I almost stormed out of his Wordsworth lecture for his rude and ignorant conclusions. The class lacked direction, but my TA made it worth it.
Warley taught reading and writing better than any prof I've ever had. Take this course.
Basically, take this class.

Christopher Warley makes reading so much fun!  The details, the knowledge and the humor of this professor are all equally intriguing.  He actually came to my graduation recital from UofT music!  A-m-a-z-i-n-g prof!
Warley makes you a better writer. He's pedantic as hell, mainly in a good way. Other than that, pretty much everything else is cringe-worthy.

before warley i hated 17th century literature... now i absolutely love it. he's a phenomenal professor and not too hard on the eyes. big thumbs up warley, thanks for bringing the enthusiasm to class, even in the darkest days of winter. he's as good as it gets.
My favourite class. I love how he stands in the very centre of the room before he's about to reveal a crucial piece of information.
Amazing professor. I absolutely LOVE his classes and I look forward to them on a weekly basis. His intelligence is inspiring as are his lectures.

I ADORE THIS PROFF - He's so genuinely involved and PASSIONATE about what he teach that you cannot help but be interested in the class. One of the few classes I have ever had where I'm excited to go and hear what new things he has to say. TOTALLY recommend this proff!
Best Prof....EVER! No one can make Milton as amazing as Warley...he is truly an English God!!!! <3
AMAZING.

Prof. Warley has been the most animated, devoted, impassioned professor I have ever had the pleasure to hear speak. His enthusiasm is infectious. He made me fall in love with John Donne. I can't imagine how incomplete my English career would have been without Warley.
He was one of the most amazing professor I've ever had in my life. Possibly the best.

A great professor and a good writer but not always a very good teacher. Unable to explain how to improve essays beyond, "Practice." Arrogant to the point of squelching class participation by any except the very thick-skinned or favourites. I can't make up my mind about whether I would take another class from him even though I learned a lot.

He was a dedicated teacher and seemed interested in the material. Clear most of the time and tried to be entertaining. I was very embarrassed for him when he "cried" in class. Overall, somewhat annoyingly pretentious and pompous. (I'm female.)

Loved him! By far the best professor I've encountered so far at UofT. He's funny, witty, entertaining, and all together just an amazing guy! If you ever get the chance to take this course, you definitely should. The way he reads Milton will change your life forever.
We should all hope to be like Christopher Warely.
i think the guy who was bothered by warley was actually just jealous.  warley is a god.  beautiful to look at and a great speaker.  awesome teacher.  take him!!!

I really enjoyed studying Milton with Warley. The secondary reading was really useful and class was always stimulating. I also thought it was really sweet when he cried as he read the last few lines of Paradise Lost. aw.
The best prof that i have ever had. He is so excited about the material that he teaches that its hard for us not to love it too. It doesnt get better than him.
No Comments

By far the best professor i have ever had. He was so enthusiastic about the material that it was infectious. Definetely worth taking again. He related to university students well, and adapted his teaching style to our needs, which made understanding the material much better.
His intelligence is sooo sexy.

Prof Warley is by far one of the best profs I have ever had. He is very enthusiastic and into what he is teaching, which makes it a plus, and makes it interesting to hear. He is also very helpful with essays and providing office hours and emailing. I would definetely take a class by him again, even if it wasnt a requirement. Prof Warley RULES!!!!!
decent enough professor, but the dude just annoyed the **** out of me so i stopped attending his class.
prof warley is amazing - one of my favourite professors at uoft. he was engaging, intelligent, hilarous and absolutely gorgeous.
No Comments
